</p>
<p>
The hyperbolic functions arise in many problems of mathematics and mathemat=
ical physics in which integrals involving <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wol=
fram.com/images/equations/HyperbolicFunctions/Inline31.svg" class=3D"inline=
formula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"64"=
 height=3D"25" alt=3D"sqrt(1+x^2)"> arise (whereas the <a href=3D"https://m=
athworld.wolfram.com/CircularFunctions.html">circular
 functions</a> involve <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equ=
ations/HyperbolicFunctions/Inline32.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"m=
ax-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"64" height=3D"25" alt=
=3D"sqrt(1-x^2)">). For instance, the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.=
com/HyperbolicSine.html">hyperbolic
 sine</a> arises in the gravitational potential of a cylinder and the calcu=
lation
 of the Roche limit. The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Hyperboli=
cCosine.html">hyperbolic cosine</a> function
 is the shape of a hanging cable (the so-called <a href=3D"https://mathworl=
d.wolfram.com/Catenary.html">catenary</a>).
 The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/HyperbolicTangent.html">hyper=
bolic tangent</a> arises in the calculation
 of and rapidity of special relativity. All three appear in the Schwarzschi=
ld metric
 using external isotropic Kruskal coordinates in general relativity. The <a=
 href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/HyperbolicSecant.html">hyperbolic
 secant</a> arises in the profile of a laminar jet. The <a href=3D"https://=
mathworld.wolfram.com/HyperbolicCotangent.html">hyperbolic
 cotangent</a> arises in the Langevin function for magnetic polarization.
</p>
